What you may not know about me... I struggled so hard in school my whole life. I had ADHD to the max. Was on a high prescription medicine from age 14-21. I graduated college by the skin of my teeth and had no idea what was to come next. I knew I didn't want to work a 9-5. I wasn't meant to fit inside a box. I said yes to every other kind of job though with hopes it would bring me to where I was meant to me. 

I'm forever thankful for the opportunities that God/ Universe has put in my path and  presented to me. I'm so proud of myself for trusting in me, that there was more for me. That I could excel in my own way. That I didn't need medication to make me smart. That I didn't need someone on my ass all the time to get by. That I knew I would figure it out. When there's a will, there's a way. I had the will and I found my way. 

Now I get to teach others how to change their story too. It brings me so much JOY.

Say yes to the opportunities right in front of you. They are there for a reason. Grateful heart this morning. 🫶🏽

I wake up grateful every day that I get to choose where I work and when I work. Today I walked into an appointment and I noticed to my right, an office full of people working at a desk at their 9 to 5, not one person seemed happy to be there. I couldn't help but have a desire to bust through the doors and tell them there's a different way. A way to live more freely. While I'm sure there are some that enjoy that structure and that stability, and this was just my perception/observation, I do believe to my core that there are many who can have and live a different way...They just don't know how because of what society has always told us. They may feel trapped in their environment and they don't even know how to take the first step. 

I never take my days for granted and I'm so happy to have choice. 

I'll continue to share, with hopes of inspiring others to live different. It's a beautiful place and way of living. I want to gift and impact as many people as possible this vessel that can provide them with the life they truly desire. 

Happy Wednesday from my cute little work space today!

I was asked to speak on stage in front of 3,000 people a few months ago. At first I was so honored and couldn't believe I was chosen.

I was so afraid to say yes, but I knew this was the next progression in my growth journey. 

Inner child AJ was so afraid of what people were going to think. I was so fearful that I wasn't good enough, worthy enough, smart enough to do this. 

I was afraid I would faint on stage, I was afraid the teleprompter would black out and I would mess up. 

I almost allowed my inner roommate to talk me out of it...

After a couple months of preparation, lots of support from my family and friends it all came together and it really happened. 

It was such a surreal experience that I will remember forever. 

It went better than I ever thought it would. It was SO MUCH FUN.

Moral of this story. There is so much greatness on the other side of fear. On the other side of fear is so much growth. You ARE worthy. You ARE smart enough. You ARE good enough. 

I'm so proud of the woman I have become and what is still in my becoming. 

Thank you @monatofficial for this opportunity. Thanks to everyone who hyped me up. Thank you to my hubby for holding me down in my fear. Ahhh I wanna do it again!!!

Let me explain. 

My Dad passed coming up on 4 years ago. We had a not fully estranged but disconnected relationship from I would say age 10-26. 

Without going into detail of our relationship earthside, I want to share about what it's like now.

I varied so much guilt for a long time when he unexpectedly passed, weeks after I was ready to mend our distant relationship. 

I was so angry at myself, at God/ Universe for taking him too soon. When it was finally our time. 

What I didn't know is that there was about to be this bond between us that was stronger than ever, that nobody would understand but us. Even though his physical being is not here. 

What I learned after he passed, after going through his journal that was gifted to me was that we were more alike than we were different. Especially spiritually. 

I immediately understood him after reading through this. And I didn't understand him the whole time he was here. 

We've had multiple conversations since he's passed. He's forgiven me, I've forgiven him. Though forgiveness isn't even what was needed. 

He gives me signs often, I feel his presence. I know he has been with me through some tough times in the last 4 years. And I know he's with me every day. 

I call him in, I invite him to be with me. There is no more boundary. He is more here than not. 

Though I wish he could physically be here, and I wish he could have met my children and watch them grow up. (The love would run deep both ways with my kids and him). It's ok. 

I've accepted this part of life. And again, I know he's here. 

So if you see me on the side of the road having conversations with the cardinals I see. Or silently listening and looking up at the sky mid conversation, now you know. I haven't lost it. I'm just having a moment with my angel.

The guilt is gone, the anger is gone. All there is is peace.

Opening yourself up to the spirit world if you believe in it doesn't have to be scary. It connects you to the divine in such a beautiful way. You only invite who you want in. 

I hope you can experience this too if you feel me on this post. Maybe you already have. If so, I get you. 

#spiritworld #angels #griefjourney #grief

9 years of love. 

9 LOVE TRUTHS AND LESSONS: 
Which do you agree with?

1. Love is a choice. If you want to be together despite your differences just keep choosing one another and it will work out.

2. Over communicate. Don't keep anything in. Be brutally honest if you have to. Communication always wins.

3. Don't ever lose your friendship. If the friendship is lost, you will lose each other. 

4. Always ask for what you need. Nobody is a mind reader. Even 9 years later. 

5. Understand each others love languages and know they can change over time. Do things for one another that may not be as important to you. 

6. Compromise. Hate to break it to you but it's part of a committed long term relationship. 

7. Never settle where you are in your relationship. Growth always matters. Find someone willing to grow with you. 

8. Fairytale love is a fairytale for a reason. Love is easy and at times can be hard. When you release fairytale love, you allow real love to come in. Love is a beautiful thing and I'm grateful to have it.

9. Relationship therapy is cool. Not just meant for when things aren't so hott. Do it now, when things are good. 

Happy Anniversary PML. I choose you forever.

So we stayed at a villa in a town called Colico, which is the most northern part of the lake. I was fearful that we would be too far away from the main spots to visit in Lake Como, but it was perfect for our family. We rented a private boat 2 days we were there and it was amazing. 

The boat took us to all the hot spots like Bellagio & Verenna. To be honest thank God we didn't end up booking a place right there. 

End of July beginning of August it was a little TOO poppin'. 

We had an amazing lunch @ghtlakecomo and another at this cute spot right before Bellagio. 

But we had the best local restaurant right at the top of our driveway at the villa that was probably our favorite. 

You all were right, the food up north in Italy doesn't compare to down south. But we really were here for the views!!! And the food was still so much better than the food here in US. 

Our favorite spot was a town called Bellano! It was not busy, kid friendly and a vibe. 

Heads up to mama's of two. The stroller we brought WAS NOT THE PLAY. I'll share more on this later.

If you're going to Como, you definitely need a couple days to see the whole lake. We were there for 5 or 6 and really enjoyed it!

I have so many more recs and pics to post!!! Ahhh!

I remember being three months postpartum after my second child and loving what I had just created, but not loving the way that I felt or the way that I looked. 

It took many daily affirmations and self-love to except the journey ahead of getting to a strong mind and body. My best, healthy self. For myself, but most importantly for my kids.

I think it's OK to love your body, which is what I have done over the last year but also want to change it and make it better at the same time. 

I get asked often how I am getting back in shape or losing weight and to be honest with you guys I haven't started to lose weight until very recently. A year postpartum. 

Let's normalize it taking time for our bodies to heal and to change. My transformation is a combination of time, lymphatic drainage massages, eating whole foods, and most meals at home, daily movement, pelvic floor and mental therapy and lots of rest.

It's a marathon not a sprint. 

It's only been a year, and I'm excited to see where my health journey continues to go from here. I love and I'm proud of how far we've come so far.

If there's ever anything you guys want to see here, please feel free to ask. I'd love to share it. 

Thank you for being on this journey with me again.

And sending so much love to all my new mama's who may feel the same. 

I've gone through this twice now. I promise it gets better. 🤍
